# Vercel Speed Insights Installation Report

## Summary
Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for the Code Compass project following the latest official Vercel documentation.

## Changes Made

### 1. Package Installation
- Added `@vercel/speed-insights` version `^2.0.0` to project dependencies
- Updated `pnpm-lock.yaml` to reflect the new dependency

### 2. Code Configuration
Modified `client/src/main.tsx`:
- Added import statement: `import { injectSpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights"`
- Called `injectSpeedInsights()` function early in the application initialization, before the QueryClient is created
- This ensures Speed Insights is properly initialized before the React application renders

## Framework-Specific Implementation
This project uses Vite + React, so per the official Vercel Speed Insights documentation, the correct approach is to:
- Use the `injectSpeedInsights()` function from `@vercel/speed-insights` 
- Call it in the main entry point (`main.tsx`) before rendering the application

This differs from Next.js apps (which use a `<SpeedInsights />` component) or React apps (which use `@vercel/speed-insights/react`).

## Verification
- ✅ Build completed successfully with `pnpm run build`
- ✅ No TypeScript errors introduced
- ✅ Code formatted with Prettier
- ✅ Tests passed (no test failures)
- ✅ Lock file properly updated

## Files Modified
1. `client/src/main.tsx` - Added Speed Insights initialization
2. `package.json` - Added dependency
3. `pnpm-lock.yaml` - Updated lock file with new dependency

## Notes
- The Speed Insights will automatically track page loads, route changes, and Web Vitals metrics
- Data will be visible in the Vercel dashboard after deployment and user visits
- No additional configuration is required as the default settings are appropriate for this project
- The project already has `@vercel/analytics` installed, so Speed Insights complements the existing analytics setup
